MAKE SURE YOUR CHILD IS ALLOWED TO ATTEND SCHOOL STARTING DAY 1

WA state laws around immunization records have changed!!! Returning students no longer have a thirty-day period to prove compliance with immunization laws before they may be excluded from public school. Additionally personal/ philosophical/religious exemptions are no longer allowed for the MMR (measles, mumps, rubella) vaccination (only religious membership exemptions will be allowed for this immunization requirement).

See Press Release about Immunizations required for class attendance http://bit.ly/31m8u8O

post_text: The Aerospace Team would like to formally invite you all to see their presentation about their recent work and future plans at 5pm on June 10 at the FHHS STEM building. We would also love it if you would spread the word and reach out to any interested parties to join as well. In particular, we are looking for anyone who may be interested in STEM pursuits, any one with engineering backgrounds, proposal experience, and especially anyone who really needs their faith in teens renewed. We are hoping that this becomes an annual event and that over time, we can build a community of support and connections that we can use to show the FH kids what it means to be in engineering at the university and professional levels. Hope to see you there as well!

April 24, 2019

San Juan Island School District Board of Directors appoints Board Member for Vacancy

Last Wednesday evening, April 24, 2019, the Board of Directors of San Juan Island School District swore in appointee Brian Moore to fill the position #5 unexpired term vacated by Jack McKenna until the election in November, 2019.

Mr. Moore accepted the position. His responsibilities on the Board of Directors began immediately. If Mr. Moore continues his interest in serving as a district director, he will be required to file for election, along with John Kurtz and T.J. Heller, during filing week, May 13, 2019 - May 17, 2019.

Contact information for all five school board members may be found on the school district website, www.sjisd.wednet.edu then select ABOUT and then BOARD,

https://www.sjisd.wednet.edu/domain/331

On Wednesday, April 17, 2019, the San Juan Island School District Board of Directors will hold a Special School Board Meeting in the High School Library, 45 Blair Ave. This is an open public meeting and is scheduled for 5:00 pm. Two interviews will be held for the school board position vacancy.

The schedule for interviews will be as follows:
Brian Moore 5:05 pm - 5:25 pm
Floyd Bourne 5:35 pm - 5:55 pm

All public comment will be heard during the “Public Comment” section of the Call to Order of the special meeting. Anyone wishing to address the board on any topic will be scheduled to speak during the public comment period by the Administrative Assistant present at the board meeting. Check in to be scheduled to speak will occur during the 15 minutes before the start of the meeting.

Thank you for your interest in our schools.

post_text:
Press Release
March 27, 2019

Snow days waived for San Juan Island School District

San Juan Island School District’s application for continuation of state support (waiver of snow days) for the February 12 and 13, 2019 school closure has been approved by the state. The district will not have to make up the two school days that were missed due to inclement weather, in accordance with the Governor’s Proclamation #19-02.

The last day of the 2018-2019 school year will remain Friday, June 14, 2019. Graduation for Friday Harbor High School seniors is Saturday, June 8, 2019.

This district-wide closure was due to a severe snow storm that created transportation conditions that were hazardous and unsafe.

post_text:
Look what's coming up next...don't miss Stepsisters! The Friday Harbor Middle School Players have been working HARD on this hilarious musical, and they need YOU to fill the seats!

Thursday: 7:30pm Pay What You Can
Friday and Saturday: 7:30pm
Sunday: 2pm

$18 Adult * $10 Student * $5 Student Rush

Visit www.sjctheatre.org, call 360.298.3210 or visit the Box Office today!

Everybody knows the Brothers Grimm’s most famous fairy tale. But what if they told it from the wrong point of view? Stepsisters tells the totally-true-and-not-at-all-made-up version of the little cinder girl. When Drew and Beth are thrown into the dungeon for conspiring against the throne, these stepsisters, who are not wicked, evil and certainly not ugly, are forced to tell their fellow prisoners the real story of what happened with Cinderella. Part flashback, part story theatre and all high-octane musical comedy, the story unfolds in ways the Grimm tale never did.

It's time for the Knowledge Bowl!

The San Juan Public Schools Foundation will host the 2019 Knowledge Bowl at the San Juan Community Theatre Monday, March 4 from 6:30 to 8:30 PM. Doors open at 6:15 PM. Tickets are $5 at the door.

This is the 25th year of the Knowledge Bowl. Student teams from Friday Harbor Middle and High Schools and Spring Street International School will take on the Soroptimists, Lions, Kiwanis, and Rotary Club in a battle for intellectual supremacy hosted by Brent Snow. The High School Jazz Band will be on hand, as well as fabulous raffle prizes, crazy costumes, a large check, and more!

It will be an evening of fun and laughter, so come join our celebration of 25 years of our island’s awesome brainpower!

post_text:
At FHES, Mrs. Danskine's Music students have been learning about a variety of musicians this year. Each month there is an "artist of the month" and students can wager a guess as to who the artist is based on clues that she shares with students in class and over the morning announcements.

Here were the clues for November's artist:
1) This artist received many awards, including Grammys, Emmys and a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
2) This artist is best known for singing and playing soul music on the piano, but he could also play the organ, trumpet, saxophone, and clarinet. He also really liked to play chess!
3) The artist was born in the state of Georgia and a song he made famous, "Georgia on my Mind" is now the official state song.

Do you know who it is? Take a peek in the picture of our students listening and watching him perform his brilliant version of "America the Beautiful".

10/16/2018 Varicella (Chickenpox) ALERT!

Three school- and preschool-aged children have CONFIRMED cases of varicella (chickenpox) on Lopez and Orcas islands, with additional possible cases awaiting evaluation from health care providers within the county.
Because chickenpox is highly contagious, we are alerting all parents of students in the county. We urge you to check your child’s immunization status to determine whether they are up to date, and to contact your primary care provider to obtain any required immunizations.

post_text:
Dear SJISD Parents,
There have been outbreaks on Orcas, Lopez and Shaw Islands of Chicken Pox. Although no Chicken Pox outbreaks have been reported on our island, it seems logical to conclude it might also happen here. Please check your child’s immunization record and if they haven’t been immunized, please get them immunized. If we have an outbreak here, any student who has not been immunized and/or does not have a doctor’s note saying they have had Chicken Pox, WILL BE EXCLUDED from school for 21 days. Let’s keep all of our students healthy.

The first semester FHHS Community Service-Learning Class will begin August 30th. This class utilizes committed adult mentors who will guide students through the completion of a service project related to community improvement – both locally and globally. This is a great opportunity for a “win-win” partnership between students and local organizations. If you have a community improvement project in mind, a fifteen minute in-class presentations time can be arranged on September 4th, 5th or 6th from 8:15-9:00 AM. Please contact Jenny Wilson at jwilson@sjisd.wednet.edu for more information.

Thank you very much for your continuing support and interest in our students!

May 22, 2018

Hello San Juan Island School District Community!
The Special Services Department would like to improve communication, collaboration, and knowledge about the “on-going” activities in Special Education with a Special Education Quarterly Newsletter. Our intent is to highlight special education laws, class activities and innovation within the special education classes and more importantly to recognize student accomplishments. The newsletter will also highlight student’s creativity through their works of art, poetry, science, and community activities. It is the hope of the Special Education Team that the newsletter will assist in further strengthening community relationships and staff collaboration with each other and the San Juan Island School District families. We look forward to hearing your feedback!
Take a peek: https://www.sjisd.wednet.edu/Page/2082

Theresa Jiminez, Special Education Director

Our combined 7th and 8th grade band attended SJMEA MS Large Group Band Festival yesterday at Mt. Vernon Christian yesterday April 17th. After coming back from Spring Break and only one combined rehearsal, they did an AMAZING job. After stuffing 70 members onto the stage with not enough space and other logistics, they problem solved and made the best of a difficult situation. All that being said, we earned a SUPERIOR rating with one judge scoring a II (Excellent) and two judges scoring a I- (Superior). The behavior and citizenship off island was very good too.

Thank you teachers again for the rehearsal time Monday and your help.

Take Care - Cart

post_text:
Dear Parent/Guardian:

In order for us to continue to improve as a school district and as a school, it is important for us to know how our parents/guardians regard the job we are doing in providing a quality education for all of our children. Your feedback is crucial for us to know what you consider our strengths and our opportunities for growth. The best way to gather this information is to survey our parents/guardians using a survey developed by the Center of Educational Effectiveness (CEE), a Bellevue, WA based research firm.

To gather this information, we are asking that you take a few minutes to complete this very important survey. The survey will only take about 10 minutes to complete.

https://www.research.net/r/SJISD-Parent

The information that we receive will be reported back to us as a building profile. This profile will provide us with information to support our building school improvement plans.

We value your input as we strive to continue to improve our school. Thank you for your feedback.

Sincerely,

Danna Diaz
Superintendent
text:
Dear Parent/Guardian:

In order for us to continue to improve as a school district and as a school, it is important for us to know how our parents/guardians regard the job we are doing in providing a quality education for all of our children. Your feedback is crucial for us to know what you consider our strengths and our opportunities for growth. The best way to gather this information is to survey our parents/guardians using a survey developed by the Center of Educational Effectiveness (CEE), a Bellevue, WA based research firm.

To gather this information, we are asking that you take a few minutes to complete this very important survey. The survey will only take about 10 minutes to complete.

https://www.research.net/r/SJISD-Parent

The information that we receive will be reported back to us as a building profile. This profile will provide us with information to support our building school improvement plans.

We value your input as we strive to continue to improve our school. Thank you for your feedback.

Sincerely,

Danna Diaz
Superintendent

On December 4, it was announced publicly at the District One meeting that our Athletic Director, Rod Turnbull, was awarded the District 1 Athletic Director of the Year Award by his District One colleagues. Rod has been an athletic director for fourteen years.

The Washington Interscholastic Activities Association (WIAA) is split into 9 Districts. All high schools from the Shoreline School District North to the Canadian Border represent District One.

The Washington Secondary School Athletic Administrators Association (WSSAAA) conference will be held on April 24 in Spokane and the district and state awards will be awarded.

FHHS Principal, Fred Woods commented, "Rod consistently displays leadership roles in his association and is an advocate for rural school districts. He manages island athletics very well while keeping the focus on academics." There are a number of people writing recommendations letters to support Rod for the state award. Congratulations, Rod!

post_text:
CONNECTING FAMILIES with Common Sense Media
----------------------
Media should work for you & work within your family values & parenting style. When media is used thoughtfully & appropriately, media can enhance daily life. But when used inappropriately or without thought, media can displace many important activities such as face-to-face interaction, family-time, outdoor-play, exercise, unplugged downtime & sleep.

By creating a Personalized Family Media Use Plan, you can be aware of when you are using media to achieve your purpose. This requires parents & users to think about what they want those purposes to be. The tool below will help you to think about media & create goals & rules that are in line with your family’s values.

Start your family media plan here: http://bit.ly/2ySGLhY

post_text:
A note from SJ Prevention Coalition:

Dear neighbors, every year at this time I forward you a survey that is used statewide by coalitions like the San Juan Island Prevention Coalition (on whose board I sit) to gather information about what community members know about drug and alcohol use and abuse, and laws regarding use, on the island. We need several hundred people to complete this survey . . . and that is hard to do.

It is so easy to get an email appeal like this and skip over it. The survey will take no more than 10 minutes. (It took me closer to three!). You may skip any questions and you may feel you do not have many answers or knowledge. But please take the time and help us anyway.

Thank you, Court Bell

Survey link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/SASAON2017

A special note to the guys. Women always fill out the survey at higher rates than men. So I will thank you in advance for helping to right the balance!

From our friends at the San Juan Prevention Coalition
-------------------------------------
Please take a moment (7 – 10 minutes) to complete the 2017 CPWI Community Survey.

ONLINE SURVEY ENGLISH
https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/SASAON2017

ONLINE SURVEY SPANISH
https://es.surveymonkey.com/r/SASASP2017

The Community Prevention and Wellness Initiative (CPWI) Community Survey is an anonymous annual statewide survey administered by all of the CPWI coalitions in Washington state.
The Community Survey captures our local San Juan Island attitudes about teen alcohol and drug use, as well as prevention programming. This data helps to inform our coalition’s strategies, as well as the state strategies.

This is an annual requirement for our funding, but more importantly, knowing the opinion of our community helps us to make informed decisions, and to help us better communicate the prevention work to the community. Last year, we were 100 surveys short of our goal, so please help us get the word out and meet our goal. Thank you.

-----DUE NOVEMBER 15----

post_text:
August 31, 2017

San Juan Island School District and San Juan Education Association
reach an impasse in Collective Bargaining

At 6:20 pm on Thursday, August 31, 2017, the San Juan Education Association (SJEA) informed the San Juan Island School District that the SJEA will hold a strike on Friday, September 1, 2017.

Schools will remain closed (San Juan Island only) for the duration of a strike. Look for updates through the online newspapers, the SJISD website, social media, and Parentlink, the District’s communication app.

The District and the union have been meeting since July and have reached an impasse. Both the District and the union have agreed on mediation.

According to SJISD Superintendent Danna Diaz, “This is a very difficult situation for our entire community. The District is committed to resolving this situation as quickly as possible. Strikes do end, and at that time we will work together again on our shared mission of educating students.”

post_text:
Sandy, the Historic Preservation Coordinator for the
Town of Friday Harbor, shared this with us! -------

Here is information about this year’s Youth Heritage Project (YHP), a fabulous one-week, (free to the student or teacher participants), field school opportunity taking place on the Tacoma waterfront this summer. Tuition, housing, meals, and transportation during the week is provided free of charge to participants.

YHP is a great opportunity for students and teachers to experience hands-on preservation, building, planning, maritime and architecture fields taught be professionals working in these disciplines. It also exposes island students to students living in different environments from all across the state. Off-island experience is always good for building confidence and perspective.

Participation is not contingent on a student and teacher going together. Interested students and teachers apply independently. The deadline for applying is May 31st.

Check it out here: http://preservewa.org/discoverwashingtonyhp.aspx

post_text:
Decision on Sixth Grade Transition Postponed until April Board Meeting

The decision by the San Juan Island School District Board of Directors on whether or not to move the sixth grade from the Friday Harbor Elementary School to Fri-day Harbor Middle School will be postponed until the regular school board meeting scheduled for April 26, 2017.

At the January 18, 2017 special school board meeting/public hearing, the elementary staff made a presentation to the board in favor of the move, citing supportive research in pedagogy and issues of crowding in the elementary school. The Board is requesting information on the impact to the 2017-2018 school year budget before making a final decision. The decision process is compounded by the uncertainty of state funding to be received by the district in the next two years. Additional information is needed for district staff to provide a clear financial projection to the board.

If there are further delays by the state legislature in approving a state budget, this decision may even be pushed back to a May special board meeting.

Dear Parent/Guardian:

In order for us to continue to improve as a school district and as a school, it is important for us to know how our parents/guardians regard the job we are doing in providing a quality education for all of our children. Your feedback is crucial for us to know what you consider our strengths and our opportunities for growth. The best way to gather this information is to survey our parents/guardians using a survey developed by the Center of Educational Effectiveness, a Bellevue, WA based research firm.

To gather this information, we are asking that you take a few minutes to complete this very important survey. The survey will only take about 15-20 minutes to complete.

The information that we receive will be reported back to us as a building profile. This profile will provide us with information to support our building school improvement plans.

We value your input as we strive to continue to improve our school. Thank you for your feed-back.

Sincerely,

Danna Diaz, Ph.D.

Superintendent, SJISD

Link to survey - https://www.research.net/r/SJISD-Parent

post_text:
Join Val Curtis, Joyce Wells and Amara Zee on Thursday, January 19th from 5:30-6:30 PM at FHMS Common to discuss how to keep up with what our children are doing online these days.

We would like to invite all parents from the Elementary, Middle and High Schools to an informational meeting about Cyber Safety.

We will share some realities our children are facing online and ways to talk to your children about being responsible.

We will share some easy guidelines you can bring into your home and apps you can use to help monitor online activity.

There will be time for conversation and questions.

text:
Join Val Curtis, Joyce Wells and Amara Zee on Thursday, January 19th from 5:30-6:30 PM at FHMS Common to discuss how to keep up with what our children are doing online these days.

We would like to invite all parents from the Elementary, Middle and High Schools to an informational meeting about Cyber Safety.

We will share some realities our children are facing online and ways to talk to your children about being responsible.

We will share some easy guidelines you can bring into your home and apps you can use to help monitor online activity.

There will be time for conversation and questions.

post_text: This posting is a friendly reminder regarding the DACA/DAPA Informational session, Saturday, July 16, 6:00 pm, San Juan Community Theatre. Pizza will be provided! Hope to see you there!
shared_text:
San Juan Island School District
July 8, 2016 at 7:33 AM ·

JULY 16, 2016
6:00 PM
SAN JUAN COMMUNITY THEATRE
DACA/DAPA UPDATE
Free Immigration Informative Event for All
On Monday, April 18, the U.S. Supreme Court finally heard oral arguments on United States v. Texas, the case involving President Obama's executive orders protecting non-criminal undocumented immigrants from deportation. Two issues are in contention with the Obama policies: the expansion of the already-existing Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA) and the creation of the new Deferred Action for Parents of Americans and Lawful Permanent Residents (DAPA). Learn the decision of the Supreme Court and how it impacts your family and our island community. Learn how we may collaborate with the San Juan Community Theatre to represent our voices and demonstrate our passion!
Keynote Speaker: Douglas Interiano

JULIO 16, 2016
6:00 PM
TEATRO COMUNITARIO DE SAN JUAN
DACA/DAPA ACTUALIZAR
Evento Informativo sobre inmigración gratis para todo
El lunes, 18 de abril, la Corte Suprema de los Estados Unidos escucho los últimos argumentos del caso, Estados Unidos v. Texas, que envuelve al Presidente Obama con la orden ejecutiva protegiendo a inmigrantes no criminales indocumentado de la deportación. Dos preguntas en consideración sobre las leyes: la expansión de la ya existencia “Acción Deferida” para la llegada de niños “DACA” y la creación de la Acción Deferida para padres de hijos/as Americanos o residentes permanentes “DAPA.” Entérate de la decisión de la Corte Suprema y como puede impactar a tu familia y a nuestra comunidad en la isla. Infórmate cómo podemos colaborar con el teatro comunitario de San Juan para representar nuestras voces y pasión.
Orador Principal: Douglas Interiano

post_text: Good morning parents & students. Beginning this week (lightly) and heavily next week. There will be road construction on the corner of guard and tucker; for those whose bus routes go through there, it might cause a bit of delay. We'll do our best to make sure students are safe and arrive to school promptly. Please plan accordingly. Thank you- Joe Gamez/ Transportation Supervisor.

post_text: Good morning parents; route 3 Beaverton valley road has broke down. That route will be delayed by 20 mins... post_text: Good morning parents and students. Today is the annual Stop Law violation survey. Last year in the state of Wa there were 542,000 reported stop paddle violations. That means a vehicle passed a school bus with their red flashing lights on and the red stop paddle out while loading or unloading students. Yikes! Please be careful out there, let's keep our students safe! -Joe Gamez, Transportation Supervisor

post_text: Friday Harbor High School senior Grace Willows' performance of the Weber Clarinet Concertino, accompanied by Dorothy Baker on the piano, took first place at the San Juan Music Educators Association woodwind solo competition, January 30, 2016. With the win, Willows, whose clarinet teacher is Sue Collado, advances to state-level competition. Congratulations Grace Willows!! https://youtu.be/auiYaocYmRk
